answers.body_markdown:
This:

    cout &lt;&lt; (false||(!false));

Evaluates to:

    cout &lt;&lt; (false||(true));

Which evaluates to:

    cout &lt;&lt; true;

Since `false || true` is `true`. The C++ representation of `true` is generally `1`, as opposed to `0` for `false`, at least by convention.

